title: Is HN Down?
text:
Obviously it isn't. But my question is why this question gets so many upvotes every time a site that isn't responding immediately to someone on the Internet, and their immediate reflex is to ask HN if it's down. Like "Yay, I'm the first to notice! Did you?"

It reminds me of when we used to get excited every time modem downloads reached a certainly high cps. It is meaningless and even expected every once in a while.

It seems like a really strange behaviour to me, and it is an HN trope by now for something that is a genuinely uninteresting question. Especially since it sometimes it's just their own ISP or whatever.

Should I be posting my download speeds to keep them excited?

Ask HN: So, what's up with Phoenix (web framework)?
text:
While I have noticed that Phoenix is a thing people are generally happy about, I was surprised to see, that it beats the Loved/Dreaded section of the current stackoverflow survey by a staggering 20% over Express and RoR.

I suspect this is due to some rather fanatical following and coordinated effort to skew the outcome. Still, I am curious, specially since the latest blog update is nearly from one year ago, which gets me at least a little suspicious in web world.

Any takers? What's the current feeling around Phoenix? Is is the end all superior fullstack framework (at least form the devs side) this survey makes it out to be?

Are CIOReview, CIOViews, Insightsuccess Scam?
text:
I was approached by CIOReview with a mail asking to feature my firm in their "Top 10 Emerging Cyber Security Company" award list. Do they actually distribute print magazines, anyone here have subscribed to them?

According to some Quora answers they are scammers and seem to print limited copies of magazines which they only ship to companies who pay them to get featured. All other promises of magazine circulation are bogus!
